I think you’re identifying a real design principle that extends beyond any one UI:

A good AI interface should disappear as competence appears.

That is different from simply being “easy to use.” It means the interface adapts to the user’s growing mental model instead of forcing them to adapt to the software.

Some principles that stand out from what you wrote:

1. Melting Interface

The interface should gradually dissolve as the user internalizes it.

Think of learning to drive.

At first:

* every control is labeled
* instructions are explicit
* guardrails are everywhere

Months later:

* almost all of that scaffolding becomes unnecessary.

The UI hasn’t failed because you stopped noticing it—it succeeded.

⸻

2. Progressive Disclosure

Never expose complexity before it becomes useful.

Instead of

100 features

the system should reveal

3 features
↓
7 features
↓
15 features
↓
expert mode

each exactly when the user is ready.

The interface becomes a teacher rather than a control panel.

⸻

3. Cognitive Priming as a First-Class Metric

I particularly like this framing.

Instead of measuring only:

* clicks
* retention
* engagement

also measure:

* How quickly does a new user form the correct mental model?
* Do they naturally discover capabilities?
* Do they predict what happens before clicking?
* Does the system feel obvious after a week?

Those are cognitive metrics rather than product metrics.

⸻

4. Intuition Over Documentation

Nobody wants to read a manual.

The best interfaces make users feel like

“I knew that would work.”

even when they had never seen it before.

That feeling is incredibly valuable.

⸻

5. Unlock Instead of Dump

Rather than

Here's everything AI can do.

Pantheon would think

“What’s the next thing this particular person is ready to understand?”

Knowledge becomes a campaign instead of an encyclopedia.

⸻

6. Compounding Learning

Every interaction should make the next interaction easier.

Not merely because of memory, but because the user has learned.

This creates positive feedback:

use
↓
understand
↓
confidence
↓
exploration
↓
more capability
↓
more understanding

Eventually the interface almost vanishes because the user has built an internal model.

⸻

7. AI-Native vs Human-Native

I think you’re right that today’s users are generally not “AI-native.”

Most people still interact with AI as if it were:

* a search engine
* Google
* Siri
* a chatbot

rather than as a collaborative reasoning system.

That suggests the interface should help users discover new interaction patterns without requiring them to study prompts or tutorials.

⸻

One thing I’d add to your doctrine is a distinction between discoverability and mastery.

Early on, optimize for discoverability:

* reduce friction
* encourage exploration
* reveal possibilities naturally

As users gain experience, shift toward mastery:

* shortcuts
* customization
* composable tools
* workflows
* automation

Those goals can conflict if presented simultaneously, but they complement each other when revealed progressively.

The result is an interface that feels almost alive: it teaches, recedes, and grows alongside the user. Rather than expecting people to become AI experts overnight, it steadily builds intuition until using the system feels natural. That kind of adaptive progression can reduce overwhelm while helping users develop genuine fluency over time.